Date:  March 25, 1993 Subject:  Re:  National Security Agency
information sought

Matthew Sean Pardo writes:

>I am doing a project on the National Security Agency, but I am having
>little luck finding much about them.  Does anyone have some pointers,
>or references?  I would really appreciate it, and would be willing to
>compile all the sources and repost.

The following is a list from my personal collection, most are still in
print and are available from local book stores (B.  Dalton, Barnes and
Noble, etc.):

1.  The Code Breakers, David Kahn, 1967, MacmIllan

2.  The Falcon and The Snowman, Robert Lindsey, 1979, Simon
    and Schuster

3.  Deep Black, William E.  Burrows, 1986, Random House

4.  Games Of Intelligence, Nigel West, 1990, Crown

5.  U.S.  Foreign Intelligence, Charles D.  Ameringer, 1990
    Lexington Books

6.  The SIGINT Secrets, Nigel West, 1986, Quill

7.  The Puzzle Palace, James Bamford, 1982, Houghton-Mifflin

8.  The U.S.  Intelligence Community, Jeffrey T.  Richelson,
    1989, Ballinger

9.  The Origin and Development Of The National Security Agency,
    George Brownell, 1981, Aegean Park Press

Many of theses books I have in either hard or softcover and the current
publisher may differ from what I have listed here, so check with your
local source for up-to-date data.

Good Luck!, Marc.

